# Fineview: Use-Case Strategy Matrix & LLD Patterns

Every technology mapped to **where it's used**, **why it's the best choice**, **what the tradeoffs are**, and the **Low-Level Design** pattern to implement it.

---

## Use Case 1: Real-Time Speech Transcription

**Objective:** Convert candidate speech to text with < 500ms latency

| Method | Latency | CPU Cost | Accuracy | Offline? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Web Speech API** ✅ | ~300ms | Zero (browser-native) | Good | ❌ |
| Whisper.cpp (WASM) | ~800ms | Very High | Excellent | ✅ |
| Server-side Whisper | ~1.5s (network) | Zero (client) | Excellent | ❌ |

**Winner: Web Speech API** — Zero client CPU, instant availability, no model download.

**Tradeoff accepted:** No offline support. Acceptable because interviews require network connectivity anyway (for WebSocket communication to server).

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Mic
    participant SpeechCapture
    participant WebSocket
    participant Server
    Mic->>SpeechCapture: Audio stream
    SpeechCapture->>SpeechCapture: Browser STT (internal)
    SpeechCapture->>WebSocket: Final transcript text (~2KB/min)
    WebSocket->>Server: Batched every 3s
```

---

## Use Case 2: Voice Activity Detection (Speaking vs Silent)

**Objective:** Detect when candidate is speaking to avoid sending silence

| Method | Latency | CPU Cost | Bundle Size | Thread |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **RMS Energy (Web Audio)** ✅ | Real-time | ~0.02ms/frame | 0 KB | Main |
| Silero VAD (ONNX/WASM) | Real-time | ~5ms/frame | ~2 MB | Worker |
| AudioWorklet + RMS | Real-time | ~0.01ms/frame | 0 KB | Audio Thread |

**Winner: RMS Energy via AnalyserNode** (now) → **AudioWorklet** (production)

**Tradeoff matrix:**

| Factor | RMS (current) | AudioWorklet (future) | Silero ONNX |
|---|---|---|---|
| Main thread impact | Minimal (0.02ms) | **Zero** | Must use Worker |
| Implementation complexity | Low | Medium | High |
| False positive rate | Higher | Higher | Very Low |
| Bundle size overhead | None | None | +2MB download |

**LLD Pattern — Current (rAF + AnalyserNode):**
```
AudioContext
  └── MediaStreamSource (mic)
       └── AnalyserNode (fftSize: 512)
            └── requestAnimationFrame loop
                 └── getFloatTimeDomainData → RMS → threshold check
```

**LLD Pattern — Production (AudioWorklet):**
```
AudioContext
  └── MediaStreamSource (mic)
       └── AudioWorkletNode('vad-processor')
            └── AudioWorkletProcessor.process()
                 └── RMS on 128-sample blocks → port.postMessage()
```

**Why AudioWorklet > rAF for production:** rAF pauses in background tabs. AudioWorklet runs on a **dedicated audio rendering thread** — guaranteed real-time, unaffected by tab visibility or main thread jank.

---

## Use Case 3: Face Detection & Monitoring

**Objective:** Detect face presence, absence, and multiple faces at 1fps

| Method | Accuracy | CPU Cost | Thread | Setup |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Skin-tone heuristic ✅ (current) | Low | ~2ms | Main | Zero |
| **MediaPipe Face Detection** (target) | High | ~15ms | **Must use Worker** | ~5MB WASM |
| TensorFlow.js BlazeFace | High | ~20ms | Worker | ~3MB |
| Server-side (send frames) | Highest | Zero (client) | N/A | High bandwidth |

**Winner: MediaPipe in Web Worker** (production) / **Skin-tone heuristic** (MVP)

**Critical tradeoff — Why NOT server-side:**
```
Client frame → Server (300KB JPEG × 1fps × 100 users)
= 30 MB/s server ingress = $$$$ and latency
                    vs
Client frame → Web Worker → JSON event (50 bytes)
= 0.005 MB/s server ingress = practically free
```

**LLD Pattern — Web Worker Architecture:**
```
Main Thread                          Worker Thread
┌──────────────────┐                ┌──────────────────┐
│ WebcamMonitor    │                │ webcamWorker.js   │
│                  │  Transferable  │                   │
│ getImageData() ──┼──ArrayBuffer──►│ MediaPipe.detect()│
│                  │                │    │               │
│ updateState() ◄──┼──{faceCount}──│    └──► result     │
└──────────────────┘   postMessage  └──────────────────┘
```

**Adaptive Degradation Decision:**
```
DeviceCapability.tier === 'high'   → 1 fps, full detection
DeviceCapability.tier === 'medium' → 1 fps, full detection
DeviceCapability.tier === 'low'    → 0.2 fps (every 5s), heuristic only
```

---

## Use Case 4: Browser Activity Tracking

**Objective:** Detect tab switches, inactivity, copy/paste in real-time

| Method | Latency | CPU Cost | Reliability |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Page Visibility API** ✅ | Instant | Zero | Very High |
| `window.blur/focus` | Instant | Zero | High |
| Polling `document.hasFocus()` | Interval-based | Low | Medium |

**Winner: All three combined** — layered detection for maximum reliability.

**No tradeoffs needed** — all methods are event-driven with zero CPU cost. The only design decision is **event batching**:

```
Event occurs → Buffer locally (max 3 seconds)
                  ↓
Timer fires  → Batch → WebSocket.send()
                  ↓
Server       → MongoDB insertMany({ writeConcern: { w: 1 } })
```

**INP impact:** All our event handlers (copy, paste, contextmenu, visibilitychange) are < 1ms. Target INP < 200ms is easily met. ✅

---

## Use Case 5: Client ↔ Server Communication

**Objective:** Real-time bidirectional messaging with auto-reconnect

| Method | Bidirectional | Latency | Reconnect | Scaling |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **WebSocket (native)** ✅ | Yes | ~5ms | Manual | Need sticky sessions |
| Socket.IO | Yes | ~8ms | Automatic | Built-in rooms/namespaces |
| SSE + POST | One-way stream | ~10ms | Automatic | Stateless |
| HTTP Polling | Simulated | ~1000ms | N/A | Stateless |

**Winner: Native WebSocket** (now) → **Socket.IO** (production)

**Tradeoff:**

| Factor | Native WebSocket | Socket.IO |
|---|---|---|
| Bundle size | 0 KB | +40 KB |
| Auto-reconnect | We built it manually | Built-in |
| Rooms/namespaces | Manual | Built-in (interviewer rooms) |
| Fallback to polling | No | Yes (critical for corporate firewalls) |
| Server complexity | Lower | Slightly higher |

**LLD Pattern — Message Protocol:**
```javascript
// Every message follows this structure:
{
  type: string,      // 'transcript' | 'monitoring_event' | 'ai_question'
  payload: object,   // The actual data
  timestamp: number  // Client-side timestamp
}
```

**Batching Strategy (bandwidth SLO: < 1.5 Mbps):**
```
Transcripts:     Send per final segment (~every 5-10s)
Monitoring:      Batch every 3 seconds
Face detection:  Send only state CHANGES (detected → lost)
VAD energy:      Do NOT send — client-only metric
```

---

## Use Case 6: Server Scaling for Concurrency

**Objective:** Handle 20–100+ simultaneous interview sessions

| Method | Max Connections/Node | Scaling Model | Complexity |
|---|---|---|---|
| Single Node.js process | ~1000 WS | Vertical only | Simple |
| **Node.js Cluster** ✅ | ~1000 × numCPUs | Horizontal (per machine) | Medium |
| PM2 (process manager) | Same as Cluster | Managed Cluster | Low |
| Kubernetes pods | Unlimited | Horizontal (across machines) | High |

**Winner: Node.js Cluster** (Phase 3) → **Kubernetes** (Phase 5 production)

**LLD Pattern — Cluster + WebSocket:**
```
                     ┌─────────────────────┐
 Nginx (ip_hash) ──► │ Primary Process     │
                     │ (no app logic)      │
                     └──┬──────┬──────┬────┘
                        │      │      │
                   fork()  fork()  fork()
                        │      │      │
                     ┌──┴──┐┌──┴──┐┌──┴──┐
                     │ W1  ││ W2  ││ W3  │
                     │ App ││ App ││ App │
                     │ +WS ││ +WS ││ +WS │
                     └──┬──┘└──┬──┘└──┬──┘
                        │      │      │
                     ┌──┴──────┴──────┴──┐
                     │ MongoDB (shared)  │
                     │ Redis (sessions)  │
                     └───────────────────┘
```

**Why `ip_hash` in Nginx:** WebSocket is a long-lived connection. Round-robin would send the upgrade request to a different worker than the initial HTTP handshake. `ip_hash` ensures the same client always reaches the same worker.

---

## Use Case 7: Data Persistence (Durability vs Speed)

**Objective:** Store interview data with appropriate durability guarantees

| Data Type | Write Frequency | Loss Tolerance | Write Concern |
|---|---|---|---|
| Monitoring events | ~10/sec per session | Some loss OK | `w: 1, j: false` |
| Transcript segments | ~0.2/sec per session | Minimal | `w: 1, j: true` |
| **Final evaluation** | Once per session | **Zero loss** | `w: "majority", j: true` |
| Session metadata | Once per session | Zero loss | `w: "majority"` |

**LLD Pattern — Tiered Write Strategy:**
```
┌─────────────────┐        ┌─────────────────┐
│ Hot Path         │        │ Cold Path        │
│ (during session) │        │ (session end)    │
│                  │        │                  │
│ events: w:1      │        │ evaluation:      │
│ transcripts: w:1 │───────►│   w:"majority"   │
│ (speed first)    │ flush  │   j:true         │
│                  │        │ (durability first)│
└─────────────────┘        └─────────────────┘
```

---

## Summary Decision Matrix

| Use Case | Current Method | Production Method | Key Tradeoff |
|---|---|---|---|
| Speech → Text | Web Speech API | Web Speech API | No offline (acceptable) |
| Voice Activity | rAF + AnalyserNode | AudioWorklet | Complexity ↑, reliability ↑↑ |
| Face Detection | Skin-tone heuristic | MediaPipe in Worker | +5MB download, accuracy ↑↑↑ |
| Browser Tracking | Visibility + Blur | Same | No tradeoff needed |
| Communication | Native WebSocket | Socket.IO | +40KB, reconnect ↑, rooms ↑ |
| Server Scaling | Single process | Cluster → K8s | Complexity ↑, capacity ↑↑↑ |
| Data Storage | — | MongoDB tiered writes | Speed vs durability per data type |
